"CORE_NARRATIVE: Current light field depth estimation fails in practical, **low angular resolution** settings due to an over-reliance on **high-resolution angular frequency spectrums**. We overcome this by introducing a **physics-based three-layer model** that extracts robust **geometric material priors**, which then drive a **dual-mask routing** architecture to resolve **EPI assumption conflicts** and enable unified depth estimation.\n\nINTRO_HOOK: Open by contrasting the theoretical success of current algorithms with the practical reality of consumer-grade cameras, highlighting how methods dependent on **high-resolution angular frequency spectrums** fundamentally fail under **low angular resolution** constraints (e.g., 9x9 sampling).\n\nGAP_BRIDGE: Transition by critiquing existing works for implicitly learning material properties via black-box networks, thereby exposing the critical need for an explicit, physics-driven decoupling mechanism that extracts **geometric material priors** independently of high-frequency spectrums.\n\nMETHOD_JUSTIFY: The **physics-based three-layer model** directly fulfills the motivation to decouple illumination, depth, and material signals, while the geometry-based classifier and **dual-mask routing** explicitly operationalize the goal of resolving **EPI assumption conflicts** without relying on high-resolution inputs.\n\nEXPERIMENT_VALIDATE: Experiments validate the motivation by demonstrating the classifier's high accuracy (89.6%) under **low angular resolution** and significant depth estimation improvements in mixed scenes, proving that our **geometric material priors** successfully bypass the dependency on **high-resolution angular frequency spectrums**.\n\nCONCLUSION_ECHO: Conclude by reiterating that the **physics-based three-layer model** and **dual-mask routing** successfully shatter the high-resolution dependency of light field depth estimation. Emphasize that this paradigm shift provides a robust foundation for deploying advanced models on practical, consumer-grade cameras operating under **low angular resolution**."